content: These 12 moves are the main variant of the whole i9 opening.
How many of you have played this pattern before in games?
usually, whenever you play i9 opening, you end up with this variant.
Move 10 blocks the black development to the left side,
and the 12th move ensures white two important key points - j7 and i8.
As you remember in the last lesson, if white only took i8 point and black could take j7 after that,
The black tactics in case of such 3x3 situations is:
do not play any of the threes unless you have to!
simply block the threatning white line.
and wait for the white's action.
that way the black's benefit is the best.
if we use a three, like this:
then the situation on the board would look like this.
and white, in return, can do its best mov eonly, that is to block 3x3 point.
and now, if we go e8, the situation becomes same
b will not play to e8
black has more choices than just e8
some moves may be much better
we can only consider using a three first, if we worry that white may block elsewhere than the 3x3 point
but in this case, we cannot see white's options than just i8.
(note that if white k6 now and black L5 the situation is still same)
white wll have to play i8 anyway
else black takes it and wins.
These 16 moves are well known theory.
Black has a big advantage all over the board.
However, it is not easy to prove sure win.
Mostly, strong players rely on the skill here, and usually still win.
Just one has to be careful, and find good sequence of connecting all sides/
There are so many ways to continue after 18th move,
Some players prefer setting up the right side, seeing which material will be left open, and then shoot them towards left side,
Some players like to develop left side first,
and seeing which left side material is left open,
the black will use them to connect right side, either through the top or bottom.
so we see white has to be passive
The style you will use in your own game, either left -> right, or right -> left, it will be yours to decide.
just remember, left side is good because of space around, and right side offers lots of connections.
the preparation moves should come before space mnove.
But in this case, both methods are acceptable.
you can see the upper bridge
we can see that likely the pair 11_19 will be blocked
and we also see the second idea through the bottom after that
using the connections from k7 and h4
we get h4 and g5 stones
even the f-line vertical cut should be considered
Therefore, the sure win here takes more time to search
do not attack without being 100% sure.
Here, we may have to deal with some counter-attack
although not necessarily wrong idea for black
This style, 21-up, goes in to positional style.
Some players prefer 19-f10, to avoid annoying counter-attacks.
but that move, although safer, has not so much space potential.
Seems only I am awake here :-)
no, your explanation is too excellent
I think, you can find your favourite 19th move by yourself,
yes, I prefer d8 to f10
But if my opponent is span, I will choose f10. Coz her counter attack is too annoying :-)
I see d8 has many fans now. :)
You can try some extraordinary ideas
now, move that connects to right side and left side at the same time
likely, white will defend right side now, and besides, the defense move must be the one that after black's d8 move doesnt force white to go f10
If white has to dfend g8 stone from f10 anyway, then black will have a dangerous attack on left side.
So, black must be careful before going to direct attack.
threes and fours are bad unless they bring win, usually.
since the left side force is useless for attack already,
we can use it to kill some white lines
and then make space move on right
span, it is not useful to extend the d8_g5 line by 1 stone, because that line is not helpful to us anyway
maybe the timing of 25 was bad
for some reason, I feel 21 and 22 stones are white's benefit
stone 22 really makes black left side material all wasted/
stone 22 kills the line 21_13, and also disables lines 23_9_1 and 23_19.
One white stone kiling three black's lines is too strong
I guess, you will need to work hard on finding perfect 19th move.
how about some externally meaningless move
just how to use it - that is the question
especially, the line i7_L10 supports that space well.
It is like a waiting move.
Doesnt really attack, it just blocks two white's potential diagonals
we realized that although black is strong, just those annoying diagonals helped white to defend each time
so why not kill those lines first before doing anything
maybe 20 should block the other side
black will get strong right side that way too
That is all about this variant. We switch to another variant now, ok?

but, it is not easy either.
Lots of annoying counter attacks have to be considered.
I did not have that much time to prove sure win.
After 1993, I changed my style of analysing.
Before that, I analysed variants until win.
After 1993, I analyse variants to satisfying patterns only, knowing that in real game I can find win there 100%.
That way I save lots of time.
So, I can only present the satisfying  structures where win is to be found in real game.
